   abstract = {The agronomic axis of the PhytoCOTE project had a primary objective of evaluating the phytosanitary pressure in the field and the risks of pesticide transfers to surface waters. But also a second objective to assess the performance of existing wine systems and propose scenarios for changing production methods and practices to reduce the use of pesticides. To do this, around forty wine-growing systems on farms belonging to different driving modes were investigated. These systems were evaluated using a multi-criteria decision support analysis method belonging to the ELECTRE methods: Electre Tri-C. Six evaluation criteria were selected on the one hand for socio-economic performance (economic profitability, workload, complexity of the wine system); on the other hand for environmental performance (phytosanitary pressure, ecotoxicity of pesticides, agro-ecological practices, level of product drift) Three scenarios for changing practices have been constructed by integrating the good practices identified in the field: a conventional reasoned scenario optimized (Reasoned-Max scenarios); two scenarios in an agro-ecological approach: Agroecology-Bio (without synthetic products) and Agroecology-conv (with optimized use of synthetic products). Electre Tri-C made it possible to affect each wine-growing system and the 3 scenarios in one of the four predefined performance categories. There is a superiority of the socio-eco-environmental performance of agroecological scenarios and biological systems. This is mainly due to a higher level of production valuation in these systems and a lower level of phytosanitary pressure with practices more favorable to strengthening biodiversity. / L' axe agronomique du projet PhytoCOTE avait un premier objectif d'évaluation de la pression phytosanitaire sur le terrain et des risques de transferts des pesticides vers les eaux de surface. Mais également un second objectif d'évaluer les performances des systèmes viticoles existants et 